# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: photogrammetry-3d
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Its name refers to the *geometrical bundles* of light rays originating from each 3D feature and converging on each camera's optical center, which are adjusted optimally according to an optimality criterion involving the corresponding image projections of all points.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Bundle adjustment is almost always used as the last step of feature-based 3D reconstruction algorithms.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Bundle adjustment was originally conceived in the field of photogrammetry during the 1950s and has increasingly been used by computer vision researchers during recent years.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Bundle adjustment boils down to minimizing the reprojection error between the image locations of observed and predicted image points, which is expressed as the sum of squares of a large number of nonlinear, real-valued functions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Thus, the minimization is achieved using nonlinear least-squares algorithms.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Of these, Levenberg–Marquardt has proven to be one of the most successful due to its ease of implementation and its use of an effective damping strategy that lends it the ability to converge quickly from a wide range of initial guesses.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] By iteratively linearizing the function to be minimized in the neighborhood of the current estimate, the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm involves the solution of linear systems termed the normal equations.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] When solving the minimization problems arising in the framework of bundle adjustment, the normal equations have a sparse block structure owing to the lack of interaction among parameters for different 3D points and cameras.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] This can be exploited to gain tremendous computational benefits by employing a sparse variant of the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm which explicitly takes advantage of the normal equations zeros pattern, avoiding storing and operating on zero-elements.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Bundle adjustment amounts to jointly refining a set of initial camera and structure parameter estimates for finding the set of parameters that most accurately predict the locations of the observed points in the set of available images.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] More formally, assume that n 3D points are seen in m views and let $\mathbf {x} _{ij}$ be the projection of the i th point on image j .
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Let $\displaystyle v_{ij}$ denote the binary variables that equal 1 if point i is visible in image j and 0 otherwise.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Assume also that each camera j is parameterized by a vector $\mathbf {a} _{j}$ and each 3D point i by a vector $\mathbf {b} _{i}$ .
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] where $\mathbf {Q} (\mathbf {a} _{j},\,\mathbf {b} _{i})$ is the predicted projection of point i on image j and $d(\mathbf {x} ,\,\mathbf {y} )$ denotes the Euclidean distance between the image points represented by vectors $\mathbf {x}$ and $\mathbf {y}$ .
[src:photogrammetry-3d/bundle-adjustment] Because the minimum is computed over many points and many images, bundle adjustment is by definition tolerant to missing image projections, and if the distance metric is chosen reasonably (e.g., Euclidean distance), bundle adjustment will also minimize a physically meaningful criterion.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Usually, the camera parameters are represented in a 3 × 4 projection matrix called the *camera matrix*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The **extrinsic parameters** define the camera *pose* (position and orientation) while the **intrinsic parameters** specify the camera image format (focal length, pixel size, and image origin).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] This process is often called **geometric camera calibration** or simply **camera calibration**, although that term may also refer to photometric camera calibration or be restricted for the estimation of the intrinsic parameters only.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] **Exterior orientation** and **interior orientation** refer to the determination of only the extrinsic and intrinsic parameters, respectively.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The classic camera calibration requires special objects in the scene, which is not required in *camera auto-calibration*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Camera resectioning is often used in the application of stereo vision where the camera projection matrices of two cameras are used to calculate the 3D world coordinates of a point viewed by both cameras.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The camera projection matrix is derived from the intrinsic and extrinsic parameters of the camera, and is often represented by the series of transformations; e.g., a matrix of camera intrinsic parameters, a 3 × 3 rotation matrix, and a translation vector.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The camera projection matrix can be used to associate points in a camera's image space with locations in 3D world space.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] In this context, we use $[u\ v\ 1]^{T}$ to represent a 2D point position in *pixel* coordinates and $[x_{w}\ y_{w}\ z_{w}\ 1]^{T}$ is used to represent a 3D point position in *world* coordinates.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] In both cases, they are represented in homogeneous coordinates (i.e. they have an additional last component, which is initially, by convention, a 1), which is the most common notation in robotics and rigid body transforms.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Referring to the pinhole camera model, a camera matrix M is used to denote a projective mapping from *world* coordinates to *pixel* coordinates.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] By dividing the matrix product by w , the theoretical value for the pixel coordinates can be found.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The K contains 5 intrinsic parameters of the specific camera model.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] These parameters encompass focal length, image sensor format, and camera principal point.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Nonlinear intrinsic parameters such as lens distortion are also important although they cannot be included in the linear camera model described by the intrinsic parameter matrix.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Many modern camera calibration algorithms estimate these intrinsic parameters as well in the form of non-linear optimisation techniques.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] This is done in the form of optimising the camera and distortion parameters in the form of what is generally known as bundle adjustment.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] $R,T$ are the **extrinsic parameters** which denote the coordinate system transformations from 3D world coordinates to 3D camera coordinates.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Equivalently, the extrinsic parameters define the position of the camera center and the camera's heading in world coordinates.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] T is the position of the origin of the world coordinate system expressed in coordinates of the camera-centered coordinate system.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] T is often mistakenly considered the position of the camera.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The position, C , of the camera expressed in world coordinates is $C=-R^{-1}T=-R^{T}T$ (since R is a rotation matrix).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] This can be verified by checking that the point $[-R^{-1}T,1]$ is transformed to $[0,0,0,1]^{T}$ , which is what is expected (since the camera's location is, in the camera's coordinates, the origin).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Camera calibration is often used as an early stage in computer vision.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] When a camera is used, light from the environment is focused on an image plane and captured.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] This process reduces the dimensions of the data taken in by the camera from three to two (light from a 3D scene is stored on a 2D image).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Each pixel on the image plane therefore corresponds to a shaft of light from the original scene.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] There are many different approaches to calculate the intrinsic and extrinsic parameters for a specific camera setup.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Zhang's method is a camera calibration method that uses traditional calibration techniques (known calibration points) and self-calibration techniques (correspondence between the calibration points when they are in different positions).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] To perform a full calibration by the Zhang method, at least three different images of the calibration target/gauge are required, either by moving the gauge or the camera itself.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] If some of the intrinsic parameters are given as data (orthogonality of the image or optical center coordinates), the number of images required can be reduced to two.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] In a first step, an approximation of the estimated projection matrix H between the calibration target and the image plane is determined using DLT method.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Subsequently, self-calibration techniques are applied to obtain the image of the absolute conic matrix.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The main contribution of Zhang's method is how to, given n poses of the calibration target, extract a constrained intrinsic matrix K , along with n instances of R and T calibration parameters.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Assume we have a homography ${\textbf {H}}$ that maps points $x_{\pi }$ on a "probe plane" $\pi$ to points x on the image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The circular points $I,J={\begin{bmatrix}1&\pm j&0\end{bmatrix}}^{\mathrm {T} }$ lie on both our probe plane $\pi$ and on the absolute conic $\Omega _{\infty }$ .
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Lying on $\Omega _{\infty }$ of course means they are also projected onto the *image* of the absolute conic (IAC) $\omega$ , thus $x_{1}^{T}\omega x_{1}=0$ and $x_{2}^{T}\omega x_{2}=0$ .
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Tsai's algorithm, a significant method in camera calibration, involves several detailed steps for accurately determining a camera's orientation and position in 3D space.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The process begins with the **initial calibration** stage, where a series of images are captured by the camera.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] These images, often featuring a known calibration pattern like a checkerboard, are used to estimate intrinsic camera parameters such as focal length and optical center.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] In some applications, variants of the chessboard target are used which are robust to partial occlusions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Such targets like the ChArUco and PuzzleBoard targets simplify the measurement of distortions in the corners of the camera sensor.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Following initial calibration, the algorithm undertakes **pose estimation**.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] This involves calculating the camera's position and orientation relative to a known object in the scene.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The process typically requires identifying specific points in the calibration pattern and solving for the camera's rotation and translation vectors.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] The final phase is the **refinement of parameters**.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] In this stage, the algorithm refines the lens distortion coefficients, addressing radial and tangential distortions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Further optimization of internal and external camera parameters is performed to enhance the calibration accuracy.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] This structured approach has positioned Tsai's Algorithm as a pivotal technique in both academic research and practical applications within robotics and industrial metrology.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Selby's camera calibration method addresses the auto-calibration of X-ray camera systems.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] X-ray camera systems, consisting of the X-ray generating tube and a solid state detector can be modelled as pinhole camera systems, comprising 9 intrinsic and extrinsic camera parameters.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/camera-resectioning] Intensity based registration based on an arbitrary X-ray image and a reference model (as a tomographic dataset) can then be used to determine the relative camera parameters without the need of a special calibration body or any ground-truth data.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] The figure below depicts two pinhole cameras looking at point **X**.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] In real cameras, the image plane is actually behind the focal center, and produces an image that is symmetric about the focal center of the lens.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Here, however, the problem is simplified by placing a *virtual image plane* in front of the focal center i.e. optical center of each camera lens to produce an image not transformed by the symmetry.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] **O**L and **O**R represent the centers of symmetry of the two cameras lenses.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] **X** represents the point of interest in both cameras.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Points **x**L and **x**R are the projections of point **X** onto the image planes.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Each camera captures a 2D image of the 3D world.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] This conversion from 3D to 2D is referred to as a perspective projection and is described by the pinhole camera model.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] It is common to model this projection operation by rays that emanate from the camera, passing through its focal center.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Each emanating ray corresponds to a single point in the image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Since the optical centers of the cameras lenses are distinct, each center projects onto a distinct point into the other camera's image plane.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] These two image points, denoted by **e**L and **e**R, are called *epipoles* or *epipolar points*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Both epipoles **e**L and **e**R in their respective image planes and both optical centers **O**L and **O**R lie on a single 3D line.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] The line **O**L–**X** is seen by the left camera as a point because it is directly in line with that camera's lens optical center.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] However, the right camera sees this line as a line in its image plane.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] That line (**e**R–**x**R) in the right camera is called an *epipolar line*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Symmetrically, the line **O**R–**X** is seen by the right camera as a point and is seen as epipolar line **e**L–**x**Lby the left camera.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] An epipolar line is a function of the position of point **X** in the 3D space, i.e. as **X** varies, a set of epipolar lines is generated in both images.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Since the 3D line **O**L–**X** passes through the optical center of the lens **O**L, the corresponding epipolar line in the right image must pass through the epipole **e**R (and correspondingly for epipolar lines in the left image).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] All epipolar lines in one image contain the epipolar point of that image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] In fact, any line which contains the epipolar point is an epipolar line since it can be derived from some 3D point **X**.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] As an alternative visualization, consider the points **X**, **O**L & **O**R that form a plane called the *epipolar plane*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] The epipolar plane intersects each camera's image plane where it forms lines—the epipolar lines.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] The epipolar plane and all epipolar lines intersect the epipoles regardless of where **X** is located.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] The epipolar geometry is simplified if the two camera image planes coincide.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Furthermore, the epipolar lines are parallel to the line **O**L–**O**R between the centers of projection, and can in practice be aligned with the horizontal axes of the two images.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] This means that for each point in one image, its corresponding point in the other image can be found by looking only along a horizontal line.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] If the cameras cannot be positioned in this way, the image coordinates from the cameras may be transformed to emulate having a common image plane.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] This process is called image rectification.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] In contrast to the conventional frame camera which uses a two-dimensional CCD, pushbroom camera adopts an array of one-dimensional CCDs to produce long continuous image strip which is called "image carpet".
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] If the one-dimensional sensor is moved over the focal plane of a static scene with fixed in place optics it is equivalent to a two-dimensional sensor other than that each part of the image is captured at a different time.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Epipolar geometry of this sensor is quite different from that of pinhole projection cameras.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] First, the epipolar line of pushbroom sensor is not straight, but hyperbola-like curve.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] Second, epipolar 'curve' pair does not exist.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/epipolar-geometry] However, in some special conditions, the epipolar geometry of the satellite images could be considered as a linear model.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In computer vision and image processing, a **feature** is a piece of information about the content of an image; typically about whether a certain region of the image has certain properties.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Features may be specific structures in the image such as points, edges or objects.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Features may also be the result of a general neighborhood operation or **feature detection** applied to the image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Other examples of features are related to motion in image sequences, or to shapes defined in terms of curves or boundaries between different image regions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] More broadly a *feature* is any piece of information that is relevant for solving the computational task related to a certain application.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] This is the same sense as feature in machine learning and pattern recognition generally, though image processing has a very sophisticated collection of features.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The feature concept is very general and the choice of features in a particular computer vision system may be highly dependent on the specific problem at hand.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] There is no universal or exact definition of what constitutes a feature, and the exact definition often depends on the problem or the type of application.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Nevertheless, a feature is typically defined as an "interesting" part of an image, and features are used as a starting point for many computer vision algorithms.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Since features are used as the starting point and main primitives for subsequent algorithms, the overall algorithm will often only be as good as its feature detector.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Consequently, the desirable property for a feature detector is *repeatability*: whether or not the same feature will be detected in two or more different images of the same scene.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Feature detection is a low-level image processing operation.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] That is, it is usually performed as the first operation on an image and examines every pixel to see if there is a feature present at that pixel.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] If this is part of a larger algorithm, then the algorithm will typically only examine the image in the region of the features.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] As a built-in pre-requisite to feature detection, the input image is usually smoothed by a Gaussian kernel in a scale-space representation and one or several feature images are computed, often expressed in terms of local image derivative operations.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Occasionally, when feature detection is computationally expensive and there are time constraints, a higher-level algorithm may be used to guide the feature detection stage so that only certain parts of the image are searched for features.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] There are many computer vision algorithms that use feature detection as the initial step, so as a result, a very large number of feature detectors have been developed.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] These vary widely in the kinds of feature detected, the computational complexity and the repeatability.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The distinction becomes relevant when the resulting detected features are relatively sparse.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Although local decisions are made, the output from a feature detection step does not need to be a binary image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The result is often represented in terms of sets of (connected or unconnected) coordinates of the image points where features have been detected, sometimes with subpixel accuracy.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] When feature extraction is done without local decision making, the result is often referred to as a *feature image*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Consequently, a feature image can be seen as an image in the sense that it is a function of the same spatial (or temporal) variables as the original image, but where the pixel values hold information about image features instead of intensity or color.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] This means that a feature image can be processed in a similar way as an ordinary image generated by an image sensor.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Feature images are also often computed as integrated step in algorithms for feature detection.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In some applications, it is not sufficient to extract only one type of feature to obtain the relevant information from the image data.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Instead, two or more different features are extracted, resulting in two or more feature descriptors at each image point.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] A common practice is to organize the information provided by all these descriptors as the elements of one single vector, commonly referred to as a **feature vector**.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The set of all possible feature vectors constitutes a **feature space**.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] A common example of feature vectors appears when each image point is to be classified as belonging to a specific class.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Assuming that each image point has a corresponding feature vector based on a suitable set of features, meaning that each class is well separated in the corresponding feature space, the classification of each image point can be done using standard classification method.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] , which are correlated with "nodes" that represent visual features.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two features.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Another and related example occurs when neural network-based processing is applied to images.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The input data fed to the neural network is often given in terms of a feature vector from each image point, where the vector is constructed from several different features extracted from the image data.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] During a learning phase, the network can itself find which combinations of different features are useful for solving the problem at hand.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Edges are points where there is a boundary (or an edge) between two image regions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In general, an edge can be of almost arbitrary shape, and may include junctions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In practice, edges are usually defined as sets of points in the image that have a strong gradient magnitude.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Furthermore, some common algorithms will then chain high gradient points together to form a more complete description of an edge.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] These algorithms usually place some constraints on the properties of an edge, such as shape, smoothness, and gradient value.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Locally, edges have a one-dimensional structure.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The terms corners and interest points are used somewhat interchangeably and refer to point-like features in an image, which have a local two-dimensional structure.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The name "Corner" arose since early algorithms first performed edge detection, and then analyzed the edges to find rapid changes in direction (corners).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] These algorithms were then developed so that explicit edge detection was no longer required, for instance by looking for high levels of curvature in the image gradient.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] It was then noticed that the so-called corners were also being detected on parts of the image that were not corners in the traditional sense (for instance a small bright spot on a dark background may be detected).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] These points are frequently known as interest points, but the term "corner" is used by tradition.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Blobs provide a complementary description of image structures in terms of regions, as opposed to corners that are more point-like.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Nevertheless, blob descriptors may often contain a preferred point (a local maximum of an operator response or a center of gravity) which means that many blob detectors may also be regarded as interest point operators.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Blob detectors can detect areas in an image that are too smooth to be detected by a corner detector.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Consider shrinking an image and then performing corner detection.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The detector will respond to points that are sharp in the shrunk image, but may be smooth in the original image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] It is at this point that the difference between a corner detector and a blob detector becomes somewhat vague.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] To a large extent, this distinction can be remedied by including an appropriate notion of scale.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Nevertheless, due to their response properties to different types of image structures at different scales, the LoG and DoH blob detectors are also mentioned in the article on corner detection.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] For elongated objects, the notion of *ridges* is a natural tool.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] A ridge descriptor computed from a grey-level image can be seen as a generalization of a medial axis.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] From a practical viewpoint, a ridge can be thought of as a one-dimensional curve that represents an axis of symmetry, and in addition has an attribute of local ridge width associated with each ridge point.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Unfortunately, however, it is algorithmically harder to extract ridge features from general classes of grey-level images than edge-, corner- or blob features.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Nevertheless, ridge descriptors are frequently used for road extraction in aerial images and for extracting blood vessels in medical images—see ridge detection.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The extraction of features are sometimes made over several scalings.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] One of these methods is the scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Once features have been detected, a local image patch around the feature can be extracted.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] This extraction may involve quite considerable amounts of image processing.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The result is known as a feature descriptor or feature vector.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Among the approaches that are used to feature description, one can mention *N*-jets and local histograms (see scale-invariant feature transform for one example of a local histogram descriptor).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In addition to such attribute information, the feature detection step by itself may also provide complementary attributes, such as the edge orientation and gradient magnitude in edge detection and the polarity and the strength of the blob in blob detection.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] A specific image feature, defined in terms of a specific structure in the image data, can often be represented in different ways.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] For example, an edge can be represented as a Boolean variable in each image point that describes whether an edge is present at that point.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Alternatively, we can instead use a representation that provides a certainty measure instead of a Boolean statement of the edge's existence and combine this with information about the orientation of the edge.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Similarly, the color of a specific region can either be represented in terms of the average color (three scalars) or a color histogram (three functions).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] When a computer vision system or computer vision algorithm is designed the choice of feature representation can be a critical issue.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In some cases, a higher level of detail in the description of a feature may be necessary for solving the problem, but this comes at the cost of having to deal with more data and more demanding processing.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Below, some of the factors which are relevant for choosing a suitable representation are discussed.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In this discussion, an instance of a feature representation is referred to as a *feature descriptor*, or simply *descriptor*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Two examples of image features are local edge orientation and local velocity in an image sequence.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In the case of orientation, the value of this feature may be more or less undefined if more than one edge are present in the corresponding neighborhood.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Local velocity is undefined if the corresponding image region does not contain any spatial variation.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] As a consequence of this observation, it may be relevant to use a feature representation that includes a measure of certainty or confidence related to the statement about the feature value.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Otherwise, it is a typical situation that the same descriptor is used to represent feature values of low certainty and feature values close to zero, with a resulting ambiguity in the interpretation of this descriptor.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Depending on the application, such an ambiguity may or may not be acceptable.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In particular, if a featured image will be used in subsequent processing, it may be a good idea to employ a feature representation that includes information about certainty or confidence.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] This enables a new feature descriptor to be computed from several descriptors, for example, computed at the same image point but at different scales, or from different but neighboring points, in terms of a weighted average where the weights are derived from the corresponding certainties.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In the simplest case, the corresponding computation can be implemented as a low-pass filtering of the featured image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The resulting feature image will, in general, be more stable to noise.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] In addition to having certainty measures included in the representation, the representation of the corresponding feature values may itself be suitable for an averaging operation or not.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Most feature representations can be averaged in practice, but only in certain cases can the resulting descriptor be given a correct interpretation in terms of a feature value.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Such representations are referred to as *averageable*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] For example, if the orientation of an edge is represented in terms of an angle, this representation must have a discontinuity where the angle wraps from its maximal value to its minimal value.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Consequently, it can happen that two similar orientations are represented by angles that have a mean that does not lie close to either of the original angles and, hence, this representation is not averageable.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] There are other representations of edge orientation, such as the structure tensor, which are averageable.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Another example relates to motion, where in some cases only the normal velocity relative to some edge can be extracted.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] If two such features have been extracted and they can be assumed to refer to same true velocity, this velocity is not given as the average of the normal velocity vectors.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Hence, normal velocity vectors are not averageable.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Instead, there are other representations of motions, using matrices or tensors, that give the true velocity in terms of an average operation of the normal velocity descriptors.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] Features detected in each image can be matched across multiple images to establish *corresponding features* such as *corresponding points*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] The algorithm is based on comparing and analyzing point correspondences between the reference image and the target image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/feature-computer-vision] If any part of the cluttered scene shares correspondences greater than the threshold, that part of the cluttered scene image is targeted and considered to include the reference object there.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] There are many variants of photogrammetry.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Another is the extraction of accurate color ranges and values representing such quantities as albedo, specular reflection, metallicity, or ambient occlusion from photographs of materials for the purposes of physically based rendering.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Close-range photogrammetry refers to the collection of photography from a lesser distance than traditional aerial (or orbital) photogrammetry.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] From its beginning with the stereoplotters used to plot contour lines on topographic maps, it now has a very wide range of uses such as sonar, radar, and lidar.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry uses methods from many disciplines, including optics and projective geometry.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Digital image capturing and photogrammetric processing includes several well defined stages, which allow the generation of 2D or 3D digital models of the object as an end product.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] The data model on the right shows what type of information can go into and come out of photogrammetric methods.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] The *3D coordinates* define the locations of object points in the 3D space.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] The *image coordinates* define the locations of the object points' images on the film or an electronic imaging device.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] The *exterior orientation* of a camera defines its location in space and its view direction.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] The *inner orientation* defines the geometric parameters of the imaging process.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] This is primarily the focal length of the lens, but can also include the description of lens distortions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Further *additional observations* play an important role: With *scale bars*, basically a known distance of two points in space, or known *fix points*, the connection to the basic measuring units is created.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Each of the four main variables can be an *input* or an *output* of a photogrammetric method.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Algorithms for photogrammetry typically attempt to minimize the sum of the squares of errors over the coordinates and relative displacements of the reference points.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] This minimization is known as bundle adjustment and is often performed using the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] A special case, called **stereophotogrammetry**, involves estimating the three-dimensional coordinates of points on an object employing measurements made in two or more photographic images taken from different positions (see stereoscopy).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Common points are identified on each image.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] A line of sight (or ray) can be constructed from the camera location to the point on the object.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] It is the intersection of these rays (triangulation) that determines the three-dimensional location of the point.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] More sophisticated algorithms can exploit other information about the scene that is known *a priori*, for example symmetries, in some cases allowing reconstructions of 3D coordinates from only one camera position.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Stereophotogrammetry is emerging as a robust non-contacting measurement technique to determine dynamic characteristics and mode shapes of non-rotating and rotating structures.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetric data can be complemented with range data from other techniques.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry is more accurate in the x and y direction while range data are generally more accurate in the z direction .
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] This range data can be supplied by techniques like LiDAR, laser scanners (using time of flight, triangulation or interferometry), white-light digitizers and any other technique that scans an area and returns x, y, z coordinates for multiple discrete points (commonly called "point clouds").
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photos can clearly define the edges of buildings when the point cloud footprint can not.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] It is beneficial to incorporate the advantages of both systems and integrate them to create a better product.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] A 3D visualization can be created by georeferencing the aerial photos and LiDAR data in the same reference frame, orthorectifying the aerial photos, and then draping the orthorectified images on top of the LiDAR grid.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] It is also possible to create digital terrain models and thus 3D visualisations using pairs (or multiples) of aerial photographs or satellite (e.g.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Techniques such as adaptive least squares stereo matching are then used to produce a dense array of correspondences which are transformed through a camera model to produce a dense array of x, y, z data which can be used to produce digital terrain model and orthoimage products.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Systems which use these techniques, e.g. the ITG system, were developed in the 1980s and 1990s but have since been supplanted by LiDAR and radar-based approaches, although these techniques may still be useful in deriving elevation models from old aerial photographs or satellite images.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry is used in fields such as topographic mapping, architecture, filmmaking, engineering, manufacturing, quality control, police investigation, cultural heritage, and geology.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Archaeologists use it to quickly produce plans of large or complex sites, and meteorologists use it to determine the wind speed of tornadoes when objective weather data cannot be obtained.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] It is also used to combine live action with computer-generated imagery in movies post-production; *The Matrix* is a good example of the use of photogrammetry in film (details are given in the DVD extras).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry was used extensively to create photorealistic environmental assets for video games including *The Vanishing of Ethan Carter* as well as EA DICE's *Star Wars Battlefront*.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] The main character of the game *Hellblade: Senua's Sacrifice* was derived from photogrammetric motion-capture models taken of actress Melina Juergens.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry is also commonly employed in collision engineering, especially with automobiles.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] When litigation for a collision occurs and engineers need to determine the exact deformation present in the vehicle, it is common for several years to have passed and the only evidence that remains is crash scene photographs taken by the police.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry is used to determine how much the car in question was deformed, which relates to the amount of energy required to produce that deformation.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] The energy can then be used to determine important information about the crash (such as the velocity at time of impact).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] This technology is also used for the inspection of submerged objects and infrastructure, thanks to its ability to produce precise, georeferenced 3D models.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] By providing reliable and reproducible metric data, underwater photogrammetry improves the monitoring of structural changes, optimizes maintenance operations, and reduces the costs associated with interventions in underwater environments.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Rectification of imagery is generally achieved by "fitting the projected images of each photograph to a set of four control points whose positions have been derived from an existing map or from ground measurements.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] "It is quite reasonable to conclude that some form of photomap will become the standard general map of the future." They go on to suggest that, "photomapping would appear to be the only way to take reasonable advantage" of future data sources like high altitude aircraft and satellite imagery.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Demonstrating the link between orthophotomapping and archaeology, historic airphotos photos were used to aid in developing a reconstruction of the Ventura mission that guided excavations of the structure's walls.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry has been as used in digital art restoration, particularly for the virtual reconstruction of historical sculptures and monuments destroyed during iconoclastic movements.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Overhead photography has been widely applied for mapping surface remains and excavation exposures at archaeological sites.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Handheld, near-nadir, overhead digital photographs have been used with geographic information systems (GIS) to record excavation exposures.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Photogrammetry is increasingly being used in maritime archaeology because of the relative ease of mapping sites compared to traditional methods, allowing the creation of 3D maps which can be rendered in virtual reality.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] A recent study applied high-resolution photogrammetry in combination with 3D scanning and quantitative morphometric analysis to compare Graeco-Roman funerary masks, enabling the re-identification of fragments and the attribution of archaeological provenience within museum collections.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] A somewhat similar application is the scanning of objects to automatically make 3D models of them.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Since photogrammetry relies on images, there are physical limitations when those images are of an object that has dark, shiny or clear surfaces.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] In those cases, the produced model often still contains gaps, so additional cleanup with software like MeshLab, netfabb or MeshMixer is often still necessary.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Alternatively, spray painting such objects with matte finish can remove any transparent or shiny qualities.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] Google Earth uses photogrammetry to create 3D imagery.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] There is also a project called Rekrei that uses photogrammetry to make 3D models of lost/stolen/broken artifacts that are then posted online.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] On Mount Stanley, an exhibition team sent out by Project Pressure created the first ever 3D model of the glacier using drone photography and GNSS technology showing a surface area decline of 29.5% between 2020 and 2024.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] High-resolution 3D point clouds derived from UAV or ground-based photogrammetry can be used to automatically or semi-automatically extract rock mass properties such as discontinuity orientations, persistence, and spacing.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/photogrammetry] There exist many software packages for photogrammetry; see comparison of photogrammetry software.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Humans perceive a great deal of information about the three-dimensional structure in their environment by moving around it.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] When the observer moves, objects around them move different amounts depending on their distance from the observer.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] This is known as motion parallax, and this depth information can be used to generate an accurate 3D representation of the world around them.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Finding structure from motion presents a similar problem to finding structure from stereo vision.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] In both instances, the correspondence between images and the reconstruction of 3D object needs to be found.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] To find correspondence between images, features such as corner points (edges with gradients in multiple directions) are tracked from one image to the next.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] One of the most widely used feature detectors is the scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] It uses the maxima from a difference-of-Gaussians (DOG) pyramid as features.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The first step in SIFT is finding a dominant gradient direction.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] To make it rotation-invariant, the descriptor is rotated to fit this orientation.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Another common feature detector is the SURF (*speeded-up robust features*).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] In SURF, the DOG is replaced with a Hessian matrix-based blob detector.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Also, instead of evaluating the gradient histograms, SURF computes for the sums of gradient components and the sums of their absolute values.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Its usage of integral images allows the features to be detected extremely quickly with high detection rate.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Therefore, comparing to SIFT, SURF is a faster feature detector with drawback of less accuracy in feature positions.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Another type of feature recently made practical for structure from motion are general curves (e.g., locally an edge with gradients in one direction), part of a technology known as *pointless SfM*, useful when point features are insufficient, common in man-made environments.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The features detected from all the images will then be matched.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] One of the matching algorithms that track features from one image to another is the Lucas–Kanade tracker.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Sometimes some of the matched features are incorrectly matched.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] This is why the matches should also be filtered.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] RANSAC (random sample consensus) is the algorithm that is usually used to remove the outlier correspondences.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] In the paper of Fischler and Bolles, RANSAC is used to solve the *location determination problem* (LDP), where the objective is to determine the points in space that project onto an image into a set of landmarks with known locations.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The feature trajectories over time are then used to reconstruct their 3D positions and the camera's motion.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] An alternative is given by so-called direct approaches, where geometric information (3D structure and camera motion) is directly estimated from the images, without intermediate abstraction to features or corners.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] There are several approaches to structure from motion.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] In incremental SfM, camera poses are solved for and added one by one to the collection.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] In global SfM, the poses of all cameras are solved for at the same time.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] A somewhat intermediate approach is out-of-core SfM, where several partial reconstructions are computed that are then integrated into a global solution.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Structure-from-motion photogrammetry with multi-view stereo provides hyperscale landform models using images acquired from a range of digital cameras and optionally a network of ground control points.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The technique is not limited in temporal frequency and can provide point cloud data comparable in density and accuracy to those generated by terrestrial and airborne laser scanning at a fraction of the cost.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Structure from motion is also useful in remote or rugged environments where terrestrial laser scanning is limited by equipment portability and airborne laser scanning is limited by terrain roughness causing loss of data and image foreshortening.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The technique has been applied in many settings such as rivers, badlands, sandy coastlines, fault zones, landslides, and coral reef settings.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] A full range of digital cameras can be utilized, including digital SLR's, compact digital cameras and even smart phones.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Generally though, higher accuracy data will be achieved with more expensive cameras, which include lenses of higher optical quality.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The technique therefore offers exciting opportunities to characterize surface topography in unprecedented detail and, with multi-temporal data, to detect elevation, position and volumetric changes that are symptomatic of earth surface processes.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Structure from motion can be placed in the context of other digital surveying methods.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Cultural heritage is present everywhere.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Its structural control, documentation and conservation is one of humanity's main duties (UNESCO).
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Under this point of view, SfM is used in order to properly estimate situations as well as planning and maintenance efforts and costs, control and restoration.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The use is accurate as only qualitative considerations are needed.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] It is fast enough to respond to the monument's immediate management needs.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] The first operational phase is an accurate preparation of the photogrammetric surveying where is established the relation between best distance from the object, focal length, the ground sampling distance (GSD) and the sensor's resolution.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] With this information the programmed photographic acquisitions must be made using vertical overlapping of at least 60%.
[src:photogrammetry-3d/structure-from-motion] Furthermore, structure-from-motion photogrammetry represents a non-invasive, highly flexible and low-cost methodology to digitalize historical documents.
